ypsies”? -- t11 The Development of German Policy in Occupied France, 1941, against the Backdrop of the War in the East -- tConclusion: Total War, Genocide, and Radicalization -- tAppendix: Comparative Table of Ranks for 1941 -- tSelected Bibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays provide current interpretations of Germany's military, economic, racial, and diplomatic policies in 1941.Nazi Germany's invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941 and events on the Eastern Front that same year were pivotal to the history of World War II. It was during this year that the radicalization of Nazi policy -- through both anall-encompassing approach to warfare and the application of genocidal practices -- became most obvious. Germany's military aggression and overtly ideological conduct, culminating in genocide against Soviet Jewry and the decimation of the Soviet population through planned starvation and brutal antipartisan policies, distinguished Operation Barbarossa-the code name for the German invasion of the Soviet Union-from all previous military campaigns in modern European history. This collection of essays, written by young scholars of seven different nationalities, provides readers with the most current interpretations of Germany's military, economic, racial, and diplomatic policies in 1941. With its breadth and its thematic focus on total war, genocide, and radicalization, this volume fills a considerable gap in English-language literature on Germany's war of annihilation against the Soviet Union and theradicalization of World War II during this critical year. Alex J. Kay is the author of Exploitation, Resettlement, Mass Murder: Political and Economic Planning for German Occupation Policy in the Soviet Union, 1940-1941 and is an independent contractor for the Ludwig Boltzmann Institute for Research on War Consequences. Jeff Rutherford is assistant professor of history at Wheeling Jesuit University, where he teaches modern European history. David Stahel is the author of Operation Barbarossa and Germany's Defeat in the East and Kiev 1941: Hitler's Battle for Supremacy in the East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEast European Studies. 4aMilitary History. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aAlex J. Kay.  aDavid Stahel.  aJeff Rutherford.  aNazi Germany.  aOperation Barbarossa.  aWorld War II.  agenocide.  amilitary aggression.  aradicalization.  atotal war.1 aFonzi, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoller, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeff Rutherford, JEFF, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJeff Rutherford, JEFF, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKay, Alex J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, Alex J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLaub, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehnstaedt, Stephan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLower, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRein, Leonid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRutherford, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRömer, Felix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStahel, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStahel, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStreit, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWettstein, Adrian E., econtribut